image.altText: Jannik Sinner holds his hands in the air after winning the 2025 Australian Open.

props.synopsis: Jannik Sinner won with a dominant 6-3, 7-6(7/4), 6-3 victory over Alexander Zverev in the men's singles final, while a protester shouted support for two women who accused Zverev of abuse during his post-match speech.

title.children: Sinner dominates Zverev to win second straight Australian Open crown

image.altText: A sea of peopel crowd together in front of a border, blocked

props.synopsis: The president floated the plan to "just clean out" the Palestinian enclave, which has been hard hit by 15 months of conflict between Israel and Hamas.

title.children: Trump says Egypt, Jordan should take in Palestinians from Gaza

image.altText: Joey Pamment stands in the sun in front of a construction site

props.synopsis: Australian small to medium enterprises expect the cost of doing business to rise this year but are keeping their sights on a reprieve from the Reserve Bank. A NAB survey found 22 per cent of businesses expect to see profitability decrease over the next year.

title.children: Businesses brace for higher costs, hope for lower rates

image.altText: Woman drinks from water bottle.

props.synopsis: The Bureau of Meteorology says temperatures in Victoria could be up to 14 degrees Celsius above the January average, and residents are warned to stay connected to emergency information throughout the day.

title.children: Victorians warned to brace for searing heat across state

image.altText: A man in a suit with black hair looking solemn

props.synopsis: South Korean prosecutors have indicted the impeached President Yoon Suk Yeol over his imposition of martial law, the main opposition party said.

title.children: South Korea's President Yoon indicted for insurrection

image.altText: Alexander Zverev and Jannik Sinner pose with their trophies

props.synopsis: There was not a lot separating Jannik Sinner and Alexander Zverev heading into the Australian Open final. But after the Italian's successful title defence, the two players appear to be on two different trajectories.

title.children: Sinner primed to own a generation after touching perfection in Aus Open final

image.altText: Jannik Sinner holds up Australian Open trophy.

props.synopsis: Jannik Sinner says he will not dwell on the controversy surrounding last year's doping violations after winning his second straight Australian Open.

title.children: Sinner has a 'clear mind' about doping case after Australian Open win

image.altText: A little girl waves an Australian flag with a big smile.

props.synopsis: Thousands of people from more than 100 countries become Australian citizens as flag-raising ceremonies take place across the nation to mark Australia Day.

title.children: 'No boundaries on what you can achieve': Thousands become citizens on Australia Day

image.altText: A group of people stand in the street holding Aboriginal flags.

props.synopsis: Thousands of people are gathering at Invasion Day rallies across the country, backing calls to abolish or change the date of Australia Day.

title.children: Protesters gather at Invasion Day rallies, calling for rethink of Australia Day

image.altText: a woman talking to the press outdoors

props.synopsis: Sussan Ley says Australia Day is a day of celebration, likening the arrival of the British First Fleet to Elon Musk's efforts to build a colony on Mars.

title.children: Ley compares First Fleet to Musk's Mars mission in Australia Day speech

image.altText: Air Vanuatu igat hevi (FB: Air Vanuatu)

props.synopsis: Plans to restart the collapsed national airline Air Vanuatu have raised concern among business and tourism leaders who say it shouldn't operate international flights again.

title.children: Vanuatu wants to reboot 'failed' national carrier, but some say 'stay away'

image.altText: A street view of a single-storey brick house next to a two-storey block of flats.

props.synopsis: More than two decades ago, the Tasmanian government sold a block of flats in a rural town. It turns out, it also "erroneously" transferred a house next door that a Sydney couple is claiming to own.

title.children: Government says it 'accidentally' transferred a house. Now it wants it back

image.altText: A roast chicken on a plate with chips, salad and glasses of iced water.

props.synopsis: Last year, the average Australian consumed more than 50 kilograms of chicken meat — almost double what we were eating in the middle of last century. So what's behind the obsession, and how sustainable is it for our food future?

title.children: From exotic treat to weekly staple, Australians are obsessed with chicken

image.altText: OUT

props.synopsis: The romantic idea of the spirit of cricket is called into question again as Tom Curran is deemed run out before being sent back in.

title.children: Spirit of cricket debate rages again as Englishman caught out of his crease

image.altText: Three police officers standing in the Adelaide parklands

props.synopsis: Sixteen far-right activists have been arrested, and one man charged with displaying a Nazi symbol, following a march in Adelaide's CBD.

title.children: Far-right activists arrested in Adelaide CBD on Australia Day

props.synopsis: Around the clock coverage of news events as they break at home and abroad.

title.children: ABC News Channel live

image.altText: Smoke plumes rising out of a building.

props.synopsis: A drone attack on one of the last functioning hospitals in El-Fasher in Sudan's Darfur region has killed 70 people and injured dozens.

title.children: Drone attack on Sudan hospital kills 70, injures dozens

image.altText: The five councillors of the Borough of Queenscliffe

props.synopsis: The Borough of Queenscliffe is in a state of upheaval, amid an investigation into allegations its CEO threatened to "take apart" a councillor. Its most popular councillor is also considering quitting.

title.children: Victoria's smallest council in turmoil just months into new term

image.altText: Cameron Diaz and Jamie Foxx running through a colourfully lit public place at night.

props.synopsis: A comedy-action flick about retired spies being pulled out of suburban bliss to save the world, Back in Action is a silly, diverting film. But it's a delight to see Cameron Diaz return to the big screen.

title.children: Cameron Diaz is Back in Action for first film in more than 10 years

image.altText: A bald man with glasses stands in front of a home with a small satellite dish on the roof

props.synopsis: Grant Vowles lives in regional Tasmania and used to be on the NBN until he switched to a satellite competitor due to frustratingly slow speeds. He'll wait and see if Labor's pledge to "finish" the network convinces him to switch back.

title.children: Labor pledges to 'finish' the NBN, but some customers have already given up

image.altText: Twenty-four 100 dollar notes and twelve 50 dollar notes on a blue mat on the floor.

props.synopsis: NSW Police search for the owner of almost $1 million that was seized as part of a drug bust.

title.children: Checked your wallet lately? Police search for owner of $1 million

image.altText: Donald Trump wears a black cap with gold lettering that says 'Make America Great Again'.

props.synopsis: As his team had promised, Trump began his presidency with shock and awe. And yet when you scratched a little deeper, there was a familiar gap between the rhetoric and the reality.

title.children: Shock, awe and a reality check in week one of Trump 2.0

image.altText: Two cars in a crash a blue car is flipped and a red one is smashed up with doors open.

props.synopsis: A 37-year-old driver was killed when two cars collided at an intersection at Ransome, with his four-year-old passenger later dying in hospital.

title.children: 4yo passenger and driver killed in car crash in Brisbane's south-east

image.altText: Image of a massive dust cloud looming over the landscape near Onslow.

props.synopsis: Witnesses at Onslow in the state's north describe the massive wave of dust as a cinematic spectacle.

title.children: Spectacular WA dust storm 'like Indiana Jones in the movies'

image.altText: Woman holds hands with two people while crying

props.synopsis: Hamas frees four women and Israel frees 200 Palestinians in the second hostage and prisoner exchange as part of the most recent ceasefire deal in Gaza.

title.children: 200 Palestinian prisoners freed as four Israeli hostages return home

image.altText: A man celebrates winning a cycling race

props.synopsis: A late crash caused panic, but Sam Welsford survived to win his third stage of this year's Tour Down Under, as Jhonatan Narváez claimed overall honours.

title.children: Sam Welsford avoids crash to win hat-trick of stages at Tour Down Under

image.altText: A Japanese man wearing a ponytail looks around in shock clutching a pillow to his naked body.

props.synopsis: Nasubi spent 18 months naked and alone in a room for a TV show. His story may seem extreme but it continues to serve as a cautionary tale about the pursuit of celebrity status, and the power of manipulation.

title.children: Naked, starved and watched by millions: Inside Japan's Truman Show 'hell'

image.altText: A sun burning bright in an orange sky above clouds on the horizon.

props.synopsis: Total fire bans will be in place for the Mallee, Wimmera, Central, North Central and South West districts, with temperatures tipped to soar to about 45 degrees Celsius in parts of the state.

title.children: Fire bans for much of Victoria on Monday amid scorching forecasts

image.altText: Two women wearing aprons gardening.

props.synopsis: Vanessa Brettell and Hannah Costello have employed and trained more than 60 migrant and refugee women through their social enterprise cafe Stepping Stone in Canberra. The pair have now been named Australia's Local Heroes for 2025.

title.children: Social enterprise cafe gives migrant and refugee women stepping stone to employment

image.altText: Nuclear cooling towers

props.synopsis: Nuclear power has been gaining more interest and attention at global climate summits, as a key weapon in the fight against climate change. But climate advocates say it's still suffering from a terrible reputation.

title.children: As Australia weighs up nuclear power, some see hope — or hype

image.altText: Donald Trump stands in front of supporters and a sign that says 'no tax on tips'

props.synopsis: The Trump administration fires about 17 independent inspectors-general at government agencies, an action some fear will remove oversight of his new administration.

title.children: Trump fires multiple watchdogs in late-night move

image.altText: A woman performs a ski jump during a competition

props.synopsis: A year out from the next Winter Olympics Australia's Laura Peel has sent a warning to her rivals with a commanding aerials victory at the latest World Cup event in Canada.

title.children: Australian skier Laura Peel claims World Cup gold

image.altText: Aerial photo of Port Hinchinbrook

props.synopsis: A hole in a soil pond wall in north Queensland has allowed potentially toxic material to seep through to two world heritage areas.

title.children: Wall dividing toxic dumping ground and Great Barrier Reef has a hole

image.altText: Three Torres Strait men in traditional dress, holding bows and arrows and a conch shell on a jetty with ocean in background.

props.synopsis: This remote corner of Australia could rival the world's top getaways. But getting travellers to the region is just one of numerous challenges facing the First Nations entrepreneurs trying to build a local industry.

title.children: Australia's 'undiscovered island' wants more tourists to visit
